\begin_layout Standard
There are several reasons we did not choose standard sphere suspension tests
 for this work.
 The first reason is that this work is focused on BD for particles above
 a no-slip wall, not on periodic (bulk) suspensions, for which most results
 are available.
 This stems from our own application interests and recent interest in active
 suspensions, in which the particles are usually above a bottom floor.
 While all of the algorithms and approaches presented here do apply to periodic
 systems (based on the PSE method of Swan), there are some optimizations
 that can be performed for periodic domains because the divergence of the
 blob-blob mobility matrix vanishes for the periodic RPY tensor.
 Also, some of the tradeoffs between the cost of different pieces of the
 solvers change, as we discuss in the conclusions – the methods here are
 really tuned to the specific geometry we study.
 The second reason is that in previous deterministic work on the rigid multiblob
 method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RigidMultiblobs"

\end_inset

 we already compared to Stokesian Dynamics and other methods for spherical
 suspensions.
 When noise is added, they key challenge is capturing the correct Gibbs-Boltzman
n equilibrium distribution, and this aspect is already tested in detail
 in the examples studied here.
 The third reason is that one of the key strengths/differences of our work
 is being able to handle non-spherical particles, so we wanted to emphasize
 that in the tests.
 There are already good methods that are specifically tailored to spherical
 suspensions, including recent boundary-integral based formulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BI_SphericalVectorHarmonics,Stokes3D_FMM,BoundaryIntegralWall_Adhikari,BoundaryIntegralGalerkin"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

