\begin_layout Standard
For the benefit of the reviewer, we not the following things.
 First, the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

alpha interpretation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the noise popularized in recent works fails in dimension higher than
 one and so does not really have a physical significance (the Ito and the
 kinetic interpetations do).
 Second, it is relatively easy to show that there is only one form of the
 equations (say if one picks Ito for the convention/notation) that is consistent
 with detailed balance, i.e., time reversibility at equilibrium, once one
 fixes either the deterministic term or the covariance of the noise.
 Third, the Strato interpretation cannot possibly be the right one for state-dep
endent noise covariance since the drift in Strato depends not just on the
 covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $\N$
\end_inset

 but on 
\begin_inset Formula $\N^{\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

, which is unphysical.
 We believe one should only use either the Ito or the kinetic interpretation
 in BD.
 Kinetic is the natural one for the Fixman midpoint scheme, and Ito for
 Euler-Maruyuama based schemes such as our RFD scheme.
\end_layout

