\begin_layout Standard
Confinement is important to this work not just for the examples but also
 in two other ways.
 First, for bulk or periodic suspensions the divergence of the RPY mobility
 matrix is zero and this simplification has been used in a number of existing
 approaches, but cannot be used with confinement.
 Second, the scalable computation of Brownian displacements, which is crucial
 in the schemes, relies on confinement (more precisely, the screening of
 hydrodynamic interactions by the wall) in this specific paper.
 For example, as of now there is no linear-scaling method to compute Brownian
 increments in an unbounded domain, which is what the simulations of Swan
 et al.
 mentioned by the reviewer do.
 The long-ranged 
\begin_inset Formula $1/r$
\end_inset

 decay of the hydrodynamic interactions and the lack of a finite domain
 to grid make this harder to do, although there are recent promising approaches
 that we hope to be able to utilize in the future 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
